b'' b': it is a dead and useless faith which has no action behind it. actions' b': prove our faith and show the genuineness of it.' b'' b'a good example of this is abraham (referred to in the james passage). hebrews' b'says that abraham was justified by faith but his faith was demonstrated' b'through his works (i.e., he obeyed what god told him to do).' b'' b"reading abraham's ``biography'' in genesis is very instructive. he was a man" b'beset by *lack* of faith a lot of the time (e.g. lying about sarah being his' b"wife on occasions; trying to fulfil god's promise on god's behalf by" b"copulating with hagar). yet it seems that god didn't evaluate him on the" b'basis of individual incidents. abraham is listed as one of the ``heroes of' b"faith'' in hebrews i.e., when it really came to the crunch, god declared" b"abraham as a man of faith. he believed god's promises." b'' b'this gives us confidence. although real faith demonstrates itself through' b'works, god is not going to judge us according to our success/failure in' b'performing works.' b'' b'``not by works of righteousness which we have done, but according to his mercy' b'he saved us, through the washing of regeneration, and renewing of the holy' b"spirit.'' (titus b'' b'amazing grace! hallelujah!' b'--' 